a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes F :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"
assumes h0 : "\<forall> x. F x = abs (x + 1) + abs (x - 5)"
shows  "range F = {y. y \<ge> 6}"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 What is the range of the function $$F(x) = |x+1|+|x-5|~?$$Express your answer in interval notation. The final Answer is [6,\infty)
 ### Proof
 We have $$F(x) = \begin{cases} -(x+1)-(x-5) &\text{if }x<-1 \\ (x+1)-(x-5) &\text{if }-1\le x<5 \\ (x+1)+(x-5) &\text{if }x\ge 5 \end{cases}.$$Simplifying, we have $$F(x) = \begin{cases} 4-2x &\text{if }x<-1 \\
 6 &\text{if }-1\le x<5 \\ 2x-4 &\text{if }x\ge 5 \end{cases}.$$For $x<-1,$ the function $4-2x$ achieves all values in $(6,\infty),$ and for $x\ge 5,$ the function $2x-4$ achieves all values in $[6,\infty).$Thus, the range of $F(x)$ is $\boxed{[6,\infty)}.$
 *)
